      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-sqa-criteria",
      "rationale": "The FEA solver (Abaqus 2022) is a commercially validated code with documented V&V history. Software QA activities include: (1) installation qualification (IQ) and operational qualification (OQ) performed per 21 CFR Part 11 requirements; (2) version-controlled simulation scripts under Git with mandatory peer review; (3) automated regression test suite (47 benchmark cases) executed at each model revision. SQA documentation package archived in the validated document management system. Achieved Gradation 3 exceeds the Gradation 2 requirement for MRL 3 Class II."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-ncv-criteria",
      "rationale": "Numerical code verification conducted via three canonical benchmark problems: (1) Hertzian contact between elastic spheres — FEA peak pressure within 0.8% of analytical solution; (2) thick-walled cylinder under internal pressure — hoop stress within 0.5% of Lamé solution; (3) elastic-plastic beam bending — load-displacement curve within 1.5% of closed-form solution. All benchmarks documented in the code verification report. Abaqus solver theory manual cross-referenced. Achieved Gradation 3 exceeds requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-disc-criteria",
      "rationale": "Discretization error quantified via systematic mesh refinement study across 5 mesh densities. Richardson extrapolation applied to peak contact stress and peak von Mises stress in the tibial tray keel. Grid Convergence Index (GCI) computed per Celik et al. (2008): GCI_fine = 2.1% for peak contact stress, GCI_fine = 1.8% for peak von Mises stress. Apparent order of convergence p = 1.94, consistent with second-order elements. Temporal discretization not applicable (quasi-static analysis). Production mesh validated at 0.5 mm edge length in contact zone. Achieved Gradation 3 meets requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-testcond-criteria",
      "rationale": "Physical test conditions replicated in the FEA model with high fidelity. ISO 14243-1 and ISO 14243-3 loading profiles applied: axial force (2600 N peak), anterior-posterior force (±200 N), flexion-extension (0–58°), internal-external rotation (±2°). Boundary conditions in the FEA model match the physical test rig constraints documented in the bench test protocol. Temperature (37°C saline environment) accounted for via temperature-dependent material properties. Tibial component alignment tolerances (±2° varus/valgus) explicitly modeled. Test condition fidelity confirmed by independent review. Achieved Gradation 3 meets requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-output-criteria",
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison performed for two primary QoIs: (1) contact stress — FEA vs. strain gauge measurements across 6 cadaveric specimens, mean absolute error 8.3%, maximum error 13.7%, within 15% acceptance threshold; (2) fatigue life ranking — FEA correctly ranked all 3 tibial tray geometries, predicted cycles within 18% of bench test medians. Statistical comparison includes 95% confidence intervals on experimental data. Uncertainty in experimental measurements quantified (strain gauge calibration uncertainty ±3.2%). Systematic bias analysis performed; no evidence of consistent over- or under-prediction. Achieved Gradation 4 exceeds Gradation 3 requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-qoi-criteria",
      "rationale": "The quantities of interest (peak contact stress on UHMWPE bearing surface, peak von Mises stress in tibial tray keel, and fatigue life index) are directly linked to the clinical failure modes of tibial component loosening and polyethylene wear. QoI selection justified by: (1) literature review of TKA retrieval analyses identifying contact stress as primary wear predictor; (2) FDA guidance document for knee implant submissions identifying fatigue life as critical performance parameter; (3) clinical advisory board review confirming QoI clinical relevance. Traceability matrix from QoI to device requirement to clinical endpoint documented. Achieved Gradation 3 meets requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-valrel-criteria",
      "rationale": "Validation activities assessed for relevance to the COU using the validation pyramid framework. Validation experiments conducted on the same tibial tray geometry and material batch as the clinical device. Loading conditions span the physiological range relevant to primary TKA patients (BMI 25–40, activity level moderate). The cadaveric specimen population (n=6, age 62–78 years) is representative of the target patient population. Validation activities cover both the verification domain (material model, mesh) and the application domain (contact stress, fatigue). Gaps between validation conditions and COU documented and assessed as not materially affecting credibility conclusions. Achieved Gradation 3 meets requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-nse-criteria",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error assessed via: (1) iterative convergence monitoring — residual force norm < 1×10⁻⁴ N for all load increments, moment residual < 1×10⁻⁴ N·mm; (2) energy balance check — artificial strain energy < 0.1% of total internal energy confirming no hourglassing; (3) contact penetration tolerance set to 0.01 mm, verified as negligible relative to contact patch dimensions; (4) automatic stabilization disabled to prevent artificial damping of contact instabilities. Solver log files archived for all production runs. Achieved Gradation 3 exceeds Gradation 2 requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-useerr-criteria",
      "rationale": "Use error risk mitigated through: (1) documented simulation protocol specifying all model setup steps, boundary condition application sequences, and post-processing procedures; (2) independent model check performed by a second qualified FEA engineer who reproduced key results within 2% using the same protocol; (3) training records confirm all analysts hold current FEA competency certification; (4) pre-submission simulation review checklist completed and signed. No use errors identified during independent check. Achieved Gradation 2 meets requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-modelform-criteria",
      "rationale": "Model form adequacy assessed for all major modeling assumptions: (1) continuum mechanics framework appropriate for polyethylene and titanium at physiological strain rates; (2) UHMWPE modeled as nonlinear elastic-plastic (isotropic hardening) — justified by comparison to published biaxial test data showing < 5% anisotropy in clinical-grade UHMWPE; (3) Ti-6Al-4V modeled as linear elastic — maximum stress 320 MPa, well below yield strength of 880 MPa; (4) bone-implant interface modeled as fully bonded — conservative assumption validated against pull-out test data; (5) quasi-static loading assumption validated by comparison to dynamic FEA for selected load cases (< 3% difference in peak stress). Model form uncertainty quantified via sensitivity analysis. Achieved Gradation 3 meets requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-inputs-criteria",
      "rationale": "Model inputs characterized with quantified uncertainty: (1) UHMWPE elastic modulus: 690 ± 35 MPa (mean ± 1σ, n=12 specimens, ASTM F2183); (2) Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus: 114 ± 2 GPa (ASTM F136 reference); (3) Applied load: ISO 14243-1 profile with ±5% measurement uncertainty documented in test rig calibration certificate; (4) Component geometry: CT-derived geometry with dimensional verification against CMM measurements, dimensional tolerance ±0.05 mm. Probabilistic sensitivity analysis (Latin Hypercube Sampling, n=500) performed to propagate input uncertainty to QoI uncertainty. 95th percentile contact stress 112 MPa, 5th percentile fatigue life index RFL = 1.08, both satisfying acceptance criteria. Achieved Gradation 3 meets requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-testsamples-criteria",
      "rationale": "Test samples used in validation experiments fully characterized and traceable: (1) Tibial tray specimens (n=6) manufactured from the same Ti-6Al-4V billet as the clinical device, lot numbers documented; (2) UHMWPE bearing inserts (n=6) from clinical-grade GUR 1020 resin, radiation crosslinked to 50 kGy, shelf life within 2 years; (3) Cadaveric femora (n=6) screened for absence of osteoarthritis, bone mineral density measured by DXA (T-score > -1.5); (4) Dimensional inspection of all specimens by CMM prior to testing; (5) Material coupon testing performed on specimens from the same lot. Sample representativeness of the target population assessed as adequate. Achieved Gradation 3 exceeds Gradation 2 requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-eqinput-criteria",
      "rationale": "Equivalency between model inputs and physical test inputs rigorously established: (1) Geometry: FEA geometry derived directly from CMM measurements of the physical specimens; surface-to-surface deviation < 0.08 mm confirmed by overlay analysis; (2) Material properties: FEA material parameters derived from mechanical testing of specimens from the same manufacturing lot as the physical test articles; (3) Loading: FEA boundary conditions replicate the physical test rig load cell measurements with < 1% discrepancy after rig compliance correction; (4) Constraints: FEA tibial tray fixation boundary conditions verified against physical rig stiffness measurements. Equivalency assessment documented in the V&V plan and confirmed by independent reviewer. Achieved Gradation 3 meets requirement."
